# Doc Freshness & Synchronization

At a **natural stopping point** (task complete, wrapping up, or before committing), briefly decide whether documentation needs updating. **Do not** run full doc rewrites on every edit — only when the changes below apply.

## Notable changes (update docs)
- New, removed, or reworked **Topics, Actions, or Subagents**.
- Changes to the **Data Model** (objects/fields).
- Changes to **FSM States** or state transitions.
- Changes to **Action Inputs/Outputs**, especially anything affecting token limits.
- Changes to **Lightning Types** or their LWC components.
- Implementation status changes (planned → built).

## Skip doc updates (usually)
- Typo/formatting-only, comments-only, or pure refactors with no user-visible change.
- Restoring prior behavior after a mistake.
- Internal renames with no architectural impact.
- Changes to customer-provided reference material.

## Which file to update
> Replace these targets with your project's doc map.

| Change type | Update |
|---|---|
| Topics, Actions, Global Instructions, Assumptions | `{{DESIGN_A}}` |
| FSM States, Percepts, Business Rules, Metrics | `{{DESIGN_B}}` |
| Object/Field Specs, Picklists, Validation Rules, ERD | `{{DESIGN_C}}` |
| Implementation steps, build progress, deploy notes | `{{BUILD_DOC}}` |
| High-level summaries, quick reference | `{{KNOWLEDGE_REF}}` |
| Master design document | `{{MASTER_DESIGN}}` |

## Checklist (lightweight)
1. **Notable change this session?** If no → stop; no doc pass.
2. **Which rows apply?** List target file(s) only.
3. **Patch** the relevant sections; avoid full rewrites unless the doc is clearly wrong end-to-end.
4. **Keep Master in sync** with the design docs it consolidates.
